r></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>Pythagorean theorem</b> or <b>Pythagoras's t=
heorem</b> is a fundamental relation in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</=
a> between the three sides of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ri=
ght_triangle" title=3D"Right triangle">right triangle</a>. It states that t=
he area of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Sq=
uare">square</a> whose side is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Hypotenuse" title=3D"Hypotenuse">hypotenuse</a> (the side opposite the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">ri=
ght angle</a>) is equal to the sum of the areas of the squares on the other=
 two sides.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESaikia2013_1-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-FOOT=
NOTESaikia2013-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theor=
em">theorem</a> can be written as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Equation" title=3D"Equation">equation</a> relating the lengths of the si=
des <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and the hyp=
otenuse <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>,=
 sometimes called the <b>Pythagorean equation</b>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sally=
-Ch3_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyth=
agorean_theorem#cite_note-Sally-Ch3-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=3Dc^{2}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>a</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>b</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>c</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=
=3Dc^{2}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/90b56b985c78deb115014efe90ce634d73dd51fa" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.505ex; width:12.983ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle a=
^{2}+b^{2}=3Dc^{2}.}"></span>
The theorem is named for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancie=
nt_Greece" title=3D"Ancient Greece">Greek</a> philosopher <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a>, bo=
rn around 570&nbsp;BC. The theorem has been <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=3D"Mathematical proof">proved</a> numer=
ous times by many different methods =E2=80=93 possibly the most for any mat=
hematical theorem. The proofs are diverse, including both <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometric</a> proofs a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">alge=
braic</a> proofs, with some dating back thousands of years.
</p><p>When <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=
=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean space</a> is represented by a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian =
coordinate system">Cartesian coordinate system</a> in <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">analytic=
 geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_distance"=
 title=3D"Euclidean distance">Euclidean distance</a> satisfies the Pythagor=
ean relation: the squared distance between two points equals the sum of squ=
ares of the difference in each coordinate between the points.
</p><p>The theorem can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generali=
zation" title=3D"Generalization">generalized</a> in various ways: to <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higher-dimensional_space" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Higher-dimensional space">higher-dimensional spaces</a>, t=
o <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometry" title=3D=
"Non-Euclidean geometry">spaces that are not Euclidean</a>, to objects that=
 are not right triangles, and to objects that are not triangles at all but =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N-dimensional" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"N-dimensional"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">n</span>-dimensional</a> solids.
</p>
