exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, with the hypotenuse being <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>. In the s=
quare on the right side, the triangles are placed such that the corners of =
the square correspond to the corners of the right angle in the triangles, f=
orming a square in the center whose sides are length <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>. Each outer square has an area=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> + <i>b</i>)<sup>2</sup></span> as wel=
l as <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>ab</i> + <i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>, with=
 <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>ab</i></span> representing the total area of t=
he four triangles. Within the big square on the left side, the four triangl=
es are moved to form two similar rectangles with sides of length <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>. These rectangles in t=
heir new position have now delineated two new squares, one having side leng=
th <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> is fo=
rmed in the bottom-left corner, and another square of side length <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> formed in the top=
-right corner. In this new position, this left side now has a square of are=
a <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> + <i>b</i>)<sup>2</sup></span> as well =
as <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>ab</i> + <i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup=
>2</sup></span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q.E.D." title=3D"Q.=
E.D.">.</a> Since both squares have the area of <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i=
>a</i> + <i>b</i>)<sup>2</sup></span> it follows that the other measure of =
the square area also equal each other such that <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i=
>ab</i> + <i>c</i><sup>2</sup> =3D</span> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ab</i>=
 + <i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span>. With the area of the=
 four triangles removed from both side of the equation what remains is <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c</i=
><sup>2</sup></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In another proof rectangles in the second box can also be placed suc=
h that both have one corner that correspond to consecutive corners of the s=
quare. In this way they also form two boxes, this time in consecutive corne=
rs, with areas <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup></span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span> which will again lead to a =
second square of with the area <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>ab</i> + <i>a</i=
><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span>.
</p><p>English mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoma=
s_Heath_(classicist)" title=3D"Thomas Heath (classicist)">Sir Thomas Heath<=
/a> gives this proof in his commentary on Proposition I.47 in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid's</a> <i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's E=
lements">Elements</a></i>, and mentions the proposals of German mathematici=
ans <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Anton_Bretschneider" titl=
e=3D"Carl Anton Bretschneider">Carl Anton Bretschneider</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Hankel" title=3D"Hermann Hankel">Herm=
ann Hankel</a> that Pythagoras may have known this proof. Heath himself fav=
ors a different proposal for a Pythagorean proof, but acknowledges from the=
 outset of his discussion "that the Greek literature which we possess belon=
ging to the first five centuries after Pythagoras contains no statement spe=
cifying this or any other particular great geometric discovery to him."<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEuclid1956351=E2=80=93352_4-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-FOOT=
NOTEEuclid1956351%E2%80%93352-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Recent scholarship has cast inc=
reasing doubt on any sort of role for Pythagoras as a creator of mathematic=
s, although debate about this continues.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_n=
ote-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
