<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_proofs_of_the_theorem=
">Other proofs of the theorem</h2></div>
<p>This theorem may have more known proofs than any other (the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_(principle)#Miscellaneous" title=3D"Law (p=
rinciple)">law</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_re=
ciprocity" title=3D"Quadratic reciprocity">quadratic reciprocity</a> being =
another contender for that distinction); the book <i>The Pythagorean Propos=
ition</i> contains 370 proofs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELoomis1940_8-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_the=
orem#cite_note-FOOTNOTELoomis1940-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_using_similar_triangl=
es">Proof using similar triangles</h3></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">In this sect=
ion, and as usual in geometry, a "word" of two capital letters, such as <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AB</span> denotes th=
e length of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_segment" titl=
e=3D"Line segment">line segment</a> defined by the points labeled with the =
letters, and not a multiplication. So, <span style=3D"font-style:normal"><s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">AB</span><sup>2</sup></span></span> denotes the square of the length <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AB</span> and not =
the product <span style=3D"font-style:normal"><span class=3D"texhtml"><span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> =C3=97 <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span><sup>2</sup></s=
pan></span>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pythagoras_similar_triangles_simplified.svg" =
class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wiki=
pedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Pythagoras_similar_triangles_simplified.svg/250px-=
Pythagoras_similar_triangles_simplified.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" d=
ata-file-height=3D"385"></a><figcaption>Proof using similar triangles</figc=
aption></figure>
<p>This proof is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prop=
ortionality_(mathematics)" title=3D"Proportionality (mathematics)">proporti=
onality</a> of the sides of three <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Similarity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similar</a> triangle=
s, that is, upon the fact that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">ratio</a> of any two corresponding sides of similar=
 triangles is the same regardless of the size of the triangles.
</p><p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ABC</s=
pan> represent a right triangle, with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">right angle</a> located at <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>, as shown on =
the figure. Draw the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altitude_(tri=
angle)" title=3D"Altitude (triangle)">altitude</a> from point <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>, and call <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span> its intersection =
with the side <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AB<=
/span>. Point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</=
span> divides the length of the hypotenuse <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> into parts <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>. The new triangle, <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ACH</span>, is <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">sim=
ilar</a> to triangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">ABC</span>, because they both have a right angle (by definition of the =
altitude), and they share the angle at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, meaning that the third angle will be the =
same in both triangles as well, marked as <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> in the figure. By a similar reasonin=
g, the triangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C=
BH</span> is also similar to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">ABC</span>. The proof of similarity of the triangles requires t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_postulate" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Triangle postulate">triangle postulate</a>: The sum of =
the angles in a triangle is two right angles, and is equivalent to the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" title=3D"Parallel =
postulate">parallel postulate</a>. Similarity of the triangles leads to the=
 equality of ratios of corresponding sides:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\begin{aligned}{\frac {BC}{AB}}&amp;=3D{\frac {BH}{BC}}\\{\fra=
c {AC}{AB}}&amp;=3D{\frac {AH}{AC}}.\end{aligned}}}">
