t=3D"540"></a><figcaption>Showing the two congruent triangles of half the a=
rea of rectangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
BDLK</span> and square <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">BAGF</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>The proof is as follows:
</p>
<ol><li>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ACB</=
span> be a right-angled triangle with right angle <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CAB</span>.</li>
<li>On each of the sides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">BC</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">AB</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">CA</span>, squares are drawn, <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CBDE</span>, <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BAGF</span>, and <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ACIH</span>, in that orde=
r. The construction of squares requires the immediately preceding theorems =
in Euclid, and depends upon the parallel postulate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gull=
berg_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyt=
hagorean_theorem#cite_note-Gullberg-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>From <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>=
, draw a line parallel to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">BD</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">CE</span>. It will perpendicularly intersect <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BC</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">DE</span> at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span>, respectively.</li>
<li>Join <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CF</span=
> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AD</span>, =
to form the triangles <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">BCF</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">BDA</span>.</li>
<li>Angles <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CAB</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BAG</spa=
n> are both right angles; therefore <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">C</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">A</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">G</span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geomet=
ry)#Collinear_points" title=3D"Line (geometry)">collinear</a>.</li>
<li>Angles <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CBD</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">FBA</spa=
n> are both right angles; therefore angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">ABD</span> equals angle <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">FBC</span>, since both are the sum of a rig=
ht angle and angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">ABC</span>.</li>
<li>Since <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AB</spa=
n> is equal to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">FB=
</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BD</span=
> is equal to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BC<=
/span> and angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
ABD</span> equals angle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">FBC</span>, triangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">ABD</span> must be congruent to triangle <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">FBC</span>.</li>
<li>Since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i>-<i>K</i>-<i>L</i></span> is a st=
raight line, parallel to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">BD</span>, then rectangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">BDLK</span> has twice the area of triangle <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ABD</span> because they share th=
e base <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BD</span> =
and have the same altitude <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">BK</span>, i.e., a line normal to their common base, connecting t=
he parallel lines <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>BD</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">AL=
</span>. (lemma 2)</li>
<li>Since <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span=
> is collinear with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">G=
</span>, and this line is parallel to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">FB</span>, then square <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">BAGF</span> must be twice in area to triangle <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">FBC</span>.</li>
<li>Therefore, rectangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">BDLK</span> must have the same area as square <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>BAGF</i> =3D <i>AB</i><sup>2</sup></span>.</li>
<li>By applying steps 3 to 10 to the other side of the figure, it can be si=
milarly shown that rectangle <span class=3D"texhtml">CKLE</span> must have =
the same area as square <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ACIH</i> =3D <i>AC</i><s=
up>2</sup></span>.</li>
<li>Adding these two results, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>AB</i><sup>2</sup>=
 + <i>AC</i><sup>2</sup> =3D</span> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>BD</i> =C3=
=97 <i>BK</i> + <i>KL</i> =C3=97 <i>KC</i></span></li>
<li>Since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>BD</i> =3D <i>KL</i></span>, <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>BD</i> =C3=97 <i>BK</i> + <i>KL</i> =C3=97 <i>KC</i> =3D<=
/span> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>BD</i>(<i>BK</i> + <i>KC</i>) =3D</span> =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>BD</i> =C3=97 <i>BC</i></span></li>
<li>Therefore, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>AB</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>AC</i><su=
p>2</sup> =3D <i>BC</i><sup>2</sup></span>, since <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>CBDE</i></span> is a square <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>BD</i> =C3=97 <i>=
BC</i> =3D <i>BC</i><sup>2</sup>)</span>.</li></ol>
<p>This proof, which appears in Euclid's <i>Elements</i> as that of Proposi=
tion&nbsp;47 in Book&nbsp;1, demonstrates that the area of the square on th=
e hypotenuse is the sum of the areas of the other two squares.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyt=
hagorean_theorem#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cit=
e_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
This is quite distinct from the proof by similarity of triangles, which is =
conjectured to be the proof that Pythagoras used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hawkin=
gp12_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyt=
hagorean_theorem#cite_note-Hawkingp12-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_=
theorem#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proofs_by_dissection_and_re=
arrangement">Proofs by dissection and rearrangement</h3></div>
<p>Another by rearrangement is given by the middle animation. A large squar=
e is formed with area <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>, =
from four identical right triangles with sides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">c</span>, fitted around a small central square. Then tw=
o rectangles are formed with sides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">b</span> by moving the triangles. Combining the smaller squar=
e with these rectangles produces two squares of areas <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>2</=
sup></span>, which must have the same area as the initial large square.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-CTK-10_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-CTK-10-17"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The third, rightmost image also gives a proof. The upper two squares=
 are divided as shown by the blue and green shading, into pieces that when =
rearranged can be made to fit in the lower square on the hypotenuse =E2=80=
=93 or conversely the large square can be divided as shown into pieces that=
 fill the other two. This way of cutting one figure into pieces and rearran=
ging them to get another figure is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dissection_problem" title=3D"Dissection problem">dissection</a>. Th=
is shows the area of the large square equals that of the two smaller ones.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-specifics_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-specifics-18"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
