<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_by_area-preserving_sh=
earing">Proof by area-preserving shearing</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Visual_proof_of_the_Pythagorean_theorem_by_ar=
ea-preserving_shearing.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Visual_proof_of_the_Py=
thagorean_theorem_by_area-preserving_shearing.gif/250px-Visual_proof_of_the=
_Pythagorean_theorem_by_area-preserving_shearing.gif" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"250" height=3D"295" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600=
" data-file-height=3D"708"></a><figcaption>Visual proof of the Pythagorean =
theorem by area-preserving shearing</figcaption></figure>
<p>As shown in the accompanying animation, area-preserving <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shear_mapping" title=3D"Shear mapping">shear mappi=
ngs</a> and translations can transform the squares on the sides adjacent to=
 the right-angle onto the square on the hypotenuse, together covering it ex=
actly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Each shear le=
aves the base and height unchanged, thus leaving the area unchanged too. Th=
e translations also leave the area unchanged, as they do not alter the shap=
es at all. Each square is first sheared into a parallelogram, and then into=
 a rectangle which can be translated onto one section of the square on the =
hypotenuse.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_algebraic_proofs">Oth=
er algebraic proofs</h3></div>
<p>A related <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garfield%27s_proof_of=
_the_Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Garfield's proof of the Pythagorean theo=
rem">proof by U.S. president James A. Garfield</a> was published before he =
was elected president; while he was a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/U.S._representative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"U.S. representative=
">U.S. representative</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Garfield_20-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_not=
e-Garfield-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-animation_21-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_no=
te-animation-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMaor2007106=E2=80=
=93107_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ythagorean_theorem#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMaor2007106%E2%80%93107-22"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Instead of a square it uses a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tr=
apezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">trapezoid</a>, which can be constructed from t=
he square in the second of the above proofs by bisecting along a diagonal o=
f the inner square, to give the trapezoid as shown in the diagram. The <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#Area" title=3D"Trapezoid">ar=
ea of the trapezoid</a> can be calculated to be half the area of the square=
, that is
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
