<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proof_using_differentials">=
Proof using differentials</h3></div>
<p>One can arrive at the Pythagorean theorem by studying how changes in a s=
ide produce a change in the hypotenuse and employing <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Staring_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Staring-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-CTK-40_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-CTK-40-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorea=
n_theorem#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The triangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">ABC</span> is a right triangle, as shown in the upper part of the diagra=
m, with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">BC</span>=
 the hypotenuse. At the same time the triangle lengths are measured as show=
n, with the hypotenuse of length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">y</span>, the side <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">AC</span> of length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">x</span> and the side <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">AB</span> of length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, as seen in the lower diagram part.
</p>
