<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Converse">Converse</h2></di=
v>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theorem#Converse" title=3D"=
Theorem">converse</a> of the theorem is also true:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sally=
-Th2.4_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Sally-Th2.4-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Given a triangle with sides of lengt=
h <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, if <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c</i><sup>2=
</sup>,</span> then the angle between sides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">right angle</a>.</p></blockquote>
<p>For any three positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_num=
bers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Real numbers">real numbers</a> <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> such that <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c</i><sup>2</su=
p></span>, there exists a triangle with sides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">c</span> as a consequence of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_inequality#Converse" title=3D"Triangle inequali=
ty">converse of the triangle inequality</a>.
</p><p>This converse appears in Euclid's <i>Elements</i> (Book I, Propositi=
on 48): "If in a triangle the square on one of the sides equals the sum of =
the squares on the remaining two sides of the triangle, then the angle cont=
ained by the remaining two sides of the triangle is right."<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythag=
orean_theorem#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It can be proved using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Law_of_cosines" title=3D"Law of cosines">law of cosines</a> or as follows:
</p><p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ABC</s=
pan> be a triangle with side lengths <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">c</span>, with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>=
b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c</i><sup>2</sup>.</span> Construct a second trian=
gle with sides of length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">b</span> containing a right angle. By the Pythagorean theorem, it follo=
ws that the hypotenuse of this triangle has length <span class=3D"nowrap">=
=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"=
><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaysty=
le \textstyle c=3D{\sqrt {a^{2}+b^{2}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
          <mi>c</mi>
          <mo>=3D</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <msqrt>
              <msup>
                <mi>a</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <msup>
                <mi>b</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
            </msqrt>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \textstyle c=
=3D{\sqrt {a^{2}+b^{2}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3ca4c5c6ba2abd637a7b39c07e7641cf6afcdb6c" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:13.605ex; height:3.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \t=
extstyle c=3D{\sqrt {a^{2}+b^{2}}}}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span>, the same as t=
he hypotenuse of the first triangle. Since both triangles' sides are the sa=
me lengths <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</spa=
n>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, the tri=
angles are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" =
title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruent</a> and must have the same angles=
. Therefore, the angle between the side of lengths <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> in the original triangle is a right =
angle.
</p><p>The above proof of the converse makes use of the Pythagorean theorem=
 itself. The converse can also be proved without assuming the Pythagorean t=
heorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyt=
hagorean_theorem#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corollary" title=3D"Corol=
lary">corollary</a> of the Pythagorean theorem's converse is a simple means=
 of determining whether a triangle is right, obtuse, or acute, as follows. =
Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> be c=
hosen to be the longest of the three sides and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
</i> + <i>b</i> &gt; <i>c</i></span> (otherwise there is no triangle accord=
ing to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_inequality" ti=
tle=3D"Triangle inequality">triangle inequality</a>). The following stateme=
nts apply:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wilczynski_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Wilczynski-=
30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</s=
up> =3D <i>c</i><sup>2</sup>,</span> then the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Right_triangle" title=3D"Right triangle">triangle is right</a>.=
</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =
&gt; <i>c</i><sup>2</sup>,</span> then the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Acute_Triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Acute Triangle">tri=
angle is acute</a>.</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =
&lt; <i>c</i><sup>2</sup>,</span> then the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Acute_and_obtuse_triangles" title=3D"Acute and obtuse triangles">t=
riangle is obtuse</a>.</li></ul>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edsger_W._Dijkstra" title=3D"Ed=
sger W. Dijkstra">Edsger W. Dijkstra</a> has stated this proposition about =
acute, right, and obtuse triangles in this language:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \operatorname {sgn} (\alpha +\beta -\gamma )=3D\operatorname {s=
gn} (a^{2}+b^{2}-c^{2}),}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>sgn</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B2<!-- =CE=B2 --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B3<!-- =CE=B3 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>sgn</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>a</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>b</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>c</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
