 function">sign function</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-31"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Consequences_and_uses_of_th=
e_theorem">Consequences and uses of the theorem</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pythagorean_triples">Pythag=
orean triples</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_triple" =
title=3D"Pythagorean triple">Pythagorean triple</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formulas_for_generating_=
Pythagorean_triples" title=3D"Formulas for generating Pythagorean triples">=
Formulas for generating Pythagorean triples</a></div>
<p>A Pythagorean triple has three positive integers <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</=
i><sup>2</sup> + <i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>. In o=
ther words, a Pythagorean triple represents the lengths of the sides of a r=
ight triangle where all three sides have integer lengths.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Sally-Ch3_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Sally-Ch3-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such a triple is c=
ommonly written <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, <i>c</i>)</spa=
n>. Some well-known examples are <span class=3D"texhtml">(3, 4, 5)</span> a=
nd <span class=3D"texhtml">(5, 12, 13)</span>.
</p><p>A primitive Pythagorean triple is one in which <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Coprime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coprime">coprime</a> (the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divisor" title=3D"Grea=
test common divisor">greatest common divisor</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> is 1).
</p><p>The following is a list of primitive Pythagorean triples with values=
 less than 100:
</p>
