/d0/Euclid_Corollary_5.svg/250px-Euclid_Corollary_5.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"291" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"380" data-file-height=3D"443"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiral_of_Theodorus" title=3D"Spiral of Theodorus">spir=
al of Theodorus</a>: A construction for line segments with lengths whose ra=
tios are the square root of a positive integer</figcaption></figure>
<p>One of the consequences of the Pythagorean theorem is that line segments=
 whose lengths are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commensurabilit=
y_(mathematics)" title=3D"Commensurability (mathematics)">incommensurable</=
a> (so the ratio of which is not a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rational_number" title=3D"Rational number">rational number</a>) can be con=
structed using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass_and_strai=
ghtedge_constructions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compass and straighte=
dge constructions">straightedge and compass</a>. Pythagoras's theorem enabl=
es construction of incommensurable lengths because the hypotenuse of a tria=
ngle is related to the sides by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square root</a> operation.
</p><p>The figure on the right shows how to construct line segments whose l=
engths are in the ratio of the square root of any positive integer.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Euclid_5_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
