<p>If Cartesian coordinates are not used, for example, if <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P=
olar coordinates">polar coordinates</a> are used in two dimensions or, in m=
ore general terms, if <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curvilinear_=
coordinates" title=3D"Curvilinear coordinates">curvilinear coordinates</a> =
are used, the formulas expressing the Euclidean distance are more complicat=
ed than the Pythagorean theorem, but can be derived from it. A typical exam=
ple where the straight-line distance between two points is converted to cur=
vilinear coordinates can be found in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Legendre_polynomials#Applications_of_Legendre_polynomials_in_physics=
" title=3D"Legendre polynomials">applications of Legendre polynomials in ph=
ysics</a>. The formulas can be discovered by using Pythagoras's theorem wit=
h the equations relating the curvilinear coordinates to Cartesian coordinat=
es. For example, the polar coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>r</i>, <=
i>=CE=B8</i>)</span> can be introduced as:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
