<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_an_axiom">As an axiom</h=
3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" =
title=3D"Parallel postulate">Parallel postulate</a></div>
<p>If the first four of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid=
ean_geometry#Axioms" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry axioms=
</a> are assumed to be true then the Pythagorean theorem is equivalent to t=
he fifth. That is, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_fift=
h_postulate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euclid's fifth postulate">Eucli=
d's fifth postulate</a> implies the Pythagorean theorem and vice-versa.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Similar_figures_on_the_thre=
e_sides">Similar figures on the three sides</h3></div>
<p>The Pythagorean theorem generalizes beyond the areas of squares on the t=
hree sides to any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similar_figures"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Similar figures">similar figures</a>. This =
was known by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocrates_of_Chios"=
 title=3D"Hippocrates of Chios">Hippocrates of Chios</a> in the 5th century=
 BC,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and was include=
d by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Eucl=
id</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elemen=
ts" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Euclid=
_VI_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyth=
agorean_theorem#cite_note-Euclid_VI-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>If one erects similar fi=
gures (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" tit=
le=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>) with corresponding sides =
on the sides of a right triangle, then the sum of the areas of the ones on =
the two smaller sides equals the area of the one on the larger side.</p></b=
lockquote>
<p>This extension assumes that the sides of the original triangle are the c=
orresponding sides of the three congruent figures (so the common ratios of =
sides between the similar figures are <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i>=E2=
=80=89:=E2=80=89<i>b</i>=E2=80=89:=E2=80=89<i>c</i></span>).<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Putz_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Putz-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While Euclid's proof o=
nly applied to convex polygons, the theorem also applies to concave polygon=
s and even to similar figures that have curved boundaries (but still with p=
art of a figure's boundary being the side of the original triangle).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Putz_45-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Putz-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The basic idea behind this generalization is that the area of a plan=
e figure is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proportionality_(mathe=
matics)" title=3D"Proportionality (mathematics)">proportional</a> to the sq=
uare of any linear dimension, and in particular is proportional to the squa=
re of the length of any side. Thus, if similar figures with areas <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span> are erected on sides with co=
rresponding lengths <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>=
 then:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\begin{aligned}&amp;{\frac {A}{a^{2}}}=3D{\frac {B}{b^{2}}}=3D=
{\frac {C}{c^{2}}}\\&amp;\quad \implies A+B=3D{\frac {a^{2}}{c^{2}}}C+{\fra=
c {b^{2}}{c^{2}}}C.\end{aligned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtable columnalign=3D"right left right left right left right lef=
t right left right left" rowspacing=3D"3pt" columnspacing=3D"0em 2em 0em 2e=
