=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> along <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>. A second triangle is formed with angle <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> oppos=
ite side <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>=
 and a side with length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">s</span> along <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">c</span>, as shown in the figure. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Th%C4%81bit_ibn_Qurra" title=3D"Th=C4=81bit ibn Qurra">Th=C4=81bit ibn=
 Qurra</a> stated that the sides of the three triangles were related as:<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Sayii_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Sayii-48"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
