hs <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> and <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">s</span> overlap l=
ess and less. When <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B8</i> =3D <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span>/2</span>, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ADB</span> becomes a rig=
ht triangle, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> + <i>s</i> =3D <i>c</i></span=
>, and the original Pythagorean theorem is regained.
</p><p>One proof observes that triangle <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">ABC</span> has the same angles as triangle <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CAD</span>, but in opposi=
te order. (The two triangles share the angle at vertex <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, both contain the angle <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span>, and so=
 also have the same third angle by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Triangle_postulate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Triangle postulate"=
>triangle postulate</a>.) Consequently, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">ABC</span> is similar to the reflection of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">CAD</span>, the triangle =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">DAC</span> in the=
 lower panel. Taking the ratio of sides opposite and adjacent to <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span>,
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\frac {c}{b}}=3D{\frac {b}{r}}.}">
