an_der_Heijden-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which are generalizations of the familiar 2-=
dimensional and 3-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
idean_spaces" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euclidean spaces">Euclidean sp=
aces</a>. For example, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_=
(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> may be conside=
red as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Ve=
ctor space">vector</a> with infinitely many components in an inner product =
space, as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" =
title=3D"Functional analysis">functional analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-L=
in_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pytha=
gorean_theorem#cite_note-Lin-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In an inner product space, the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicularity</a> =
is replaced by the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orth=
ogonal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orthogonal">orthogonality</a>: two v=
ectors <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<b>w</b></span> are orthogonal if their inner product <span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline m=
we-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.=
