<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Non-Euclidean_geometry">Non=
-Euclidean geometry</h3></div>
<p>The Pythagorean theorem is derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Foundations_of_geometry" title=3D"Foundations of geometry">axi=
oms</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" tit=
le=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, and in fact, were the Pyt=
hagorean theorem to fail for some right triangle, then the plane in which t=
his triangle is contained cannot be Euclidean. More precisely, the Pythagor=
ean theorem <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate#Equ=
ivalent_properties" title=3D"Parallel postulate">implies, and is implied by=
, Euclid's Parallel (Fifth) Postulate</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Parallel_60-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_=
theorem#cite_note-Parallel-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pruss_61-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_the=
orem#cite_note-Pruss-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Thus, right triangles in a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Non-Euclidea=
n geometry">non-Euclidean geometry</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawking20=
054_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyth=
agorean_theorem#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHawking20054-62"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> do not satis=
fy the Pythagorean theorem. For example, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Spherical_geometry" title=3D"Spherical geometry">spherical geomet=
ry</a>, all three sides of the right triangle (say <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>) bounding an octant of the unit sphere hav=
e length equal to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>=CF=80</span>/2, and all its angles are right angles, which violates the P=
ythagorean theorem because <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <=
i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D 2<i>c</i><sup>2</sup> &gt; <i>c</i><sup>2</sup></sp=
an>.
</p><p>Here two cases of non-Euclidean geometry are considered=E2=80=94<a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_geometry" title=3D"Spherical=
 geometry">spherical geometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic plane geo=
metry</a>; in each case, as in the Euclidean case for non-right triangles, =
the result replacing the Pythagorean theorem follows from the appropriate l=
aw of cosines.
</p><p>However, the Pythagorean theorem remains true in hyperbolic geometry=
 and elliptic geometry if the condition that the triangle be right is repla=
ced with the condition that two of the angles sum to the third, say <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i> + <i>B</i> =3D <i>C</i></span>. The sides are the=
n related as follows: the sum of the areas of the circles with diameters <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> equals the are=
a of the circle with diameter <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">c</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-63"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Spherical_geometry">Spheric=
al geometry</h4></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Triangle_sph%C3%A9rique.svg" class=3D"mw-file=
