<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plimpton_322.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Pl=
impton_322.jpg/250px-Plimpton_322.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"173" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1246" data-file-he=
ight=3D"863"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
limpton_322" title=3D"Plimpton 322">Plimpton 322 tablet</a> records <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_triple" title=3D"Pythagorean =
triple">Pythagorean triples</a> from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Babylonia" title=3D"Babylonia">Babylonian</a> times.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Neugebauer_69-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Neugebauer-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></f=
igure>
<p>There is debate whether the Pythagorean theorem was discovered once, or =
many times in many places, and the date of first discovery is uncertain, as=
 is the date of the first proof. The history of the theorem can be divided =
into four parts: knowledge of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyth=
agorean_triples" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pythagorean triples">Pythag=
orean triples</a>, knowledge of the relationship among the sides of a right=
 triangle, knowledge of the relationships among adjacent angles, and proofs=
 of the theorem within some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deduct=
ive_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Deductive system">deductive syst=
em</a>.
</p><p>Written <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr> 1800<span class=3D"nowrap">&=
nbsp;</span>BC, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egypt" title=
=3D"Egypt">Egyptian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Kin=
gdom_of_Egypt" title=3D"Middle Kingdom of Egypt">Middle Kingdom</a> <i><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin_Papyrus_6619" title=3D"Berlin P=
apyrus 6619">Berlin Papyrus 6619</a></i> includes a problem whose solution =
is the Pythagorean triple 6:8:10, but the problem does not mention a triang=
le. According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plutarch" title=
=3D"Plutarch">Plutarch</a>, the ancient Egyptians did know about the 3:4:5 =
right triangle, identifying its sides with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Osiris" title=3D"Osiris">Osiris</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Isis" title=3D"Isis">Isis</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Horus" title=3D"Horus">Horus</a> respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythag=
orean_theorem#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Historians of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" =
title=3D"Mesopotamia">Mesopotamian</a> mathematics have concluded that the =
Pythagorean rule was in widespread use during the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Old_Babylonian_period" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Old B=
abylonian period">Old Babylonian period</a> (20th to 16th centuries BC), ov=
er a thousand years before <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythago=
ras" title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a> was born.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_the=
orem#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-72"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Mesopotamian tablet <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plimpton_322" title=3D"Plimpton 322"=
>Plimpton 322</a></i>, written near <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Larsa" title=3D"Larsa">Larsa</a> also <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr> 180=
0<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>BC, contains entries that can be inter=
preted as the sides and diagonals of 15 different Pythagorean triples.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERobson2001_75-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-FOOTNOTERobson2001-=
75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Another tablet from a similar time, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/YBC_7289" title=3D"YBC 7289">YBC 7289</a>, calculates the=
 diagonal of a square or, equivalently, or an isosceles right triangle.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India" title=3D"India">I=
ndia</a>, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baudhayana" title=
=3D"Baudhayana">Baudhayana</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shu=
lba_Sutras" title=3D"Shulba Sutras">Shulba Sutra</a></i>, the dates of whic=
h are given variously as between the 8th and 5th century BC,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pytha=
gorean_theorem#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> contains a list of Pythagorean tri=
ples and a statement of the Pythagorean theorem, both in the special case o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isosceles_triangle" title=3D=
"Isosceles triangle">isosceles</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Isosceles_right_triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isosceles right t=
riangle">right triangle</a> and in the general case, as does the <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apastamba" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Apastamba">Apastamba</a> Shulba Sutra</i> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr>=
<span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89600&nbsp;BC</span>).<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine_Empire" title=3D"=
Byzantine Empire">Byzantine</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ne=
oplatonism" title=3D"Neoplatonism">Neoplatonic</a> philosopher and mathemat=
ician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proclus" title=3D"Proclus">P=
roclus</a>, writing in the fifth century AD, states two arithmetic rules, "=
one of them attributed to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato" t=
itle=3D"Plato">Plato</a>, the other to Pythagoras",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_th=
eorem#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for generating special Pythagorean triples.=
 The rule attributed to Pythagoras (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span st=
yle=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89570</span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span styl=
e=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89495&nbsp;BC</span>) starts from an <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Parity (=
mathematics)">odd number</a> and produces a triple with leg and hypotenuse =
differing by one unit; the rule attributed to Plato (428/427 or 424/423 =E2=
=80=93 348/347&nbsp;BC) starts from an even number and produces a triple wi=
th leg and hypotenuse differing by two units. According to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T._L._Heath" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"T. L. =
Heath">Thomas L. Heath</a> (1861=E2=80=931940), no specific attribution of =
the theorem to Pythagoras exists in the surviving Greek literature from the=
 five centuries after Pythagoras lived.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_n=
ote-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> However, when authors such as <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Plutarch" title=3D"Plutarch">Plutarch</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cicero" title=3D"Cicero">Cicero</a> attributed =
the theorem to Pythagoras, they did so in a way which suggests that the att=
ribution was widely known and undoubted.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-heath144_82-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_th=
eorem#cite_note-heath144-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Heath3_83-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theo=
rem#cite_note-Heath3-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Classics" title=3D"Classics">Classicist</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Kurt_von_Fritz" title=3D"Kurt von Fritz">Kurt von Fritz</a> wr=
ote, "Whether this formula is rightly attributed to Pythagoras personally&n=
bsp;... one can safely assume that it belongs to the very oldest period of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoreanism" title=3D"Pythagore=
anism">Pythagorean mathematics</a>."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFritz194525=
2_84-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythag=
orean_theorem#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFritz1945252-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Around 300&nbs=
p;BC, in Euclid's <i>Elements</i>, the oldest extant <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">axiomatic proof</a> o=
f the theorem is presented.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Aaboe_85-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-=
Aaboe-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Chinese_pythagoras.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Chinese_pythagoras.jpg=
/250px-Chinese_pythagoras.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"1=
36" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"871" data-file-height=3D"4=
75"></a><figcaption>Geometric proof of the Pythagorean theorem from the <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhoubi_Suanjing" title=3D"Zhoubi S=
uanjing">Zhoubi Suanjing</a></i></figcaption></figure>
<p>With contents known much earlier, but in surviving texts dating from rou=
ghly the 1st century BC, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China=
" title=3D"China">Chinese</a> text <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Zhoubi_Suanjing" title=3D"Zhoubi Suanjing">Zhoubi Suanjing</a></i> (=E5=
=91=A8=E9=AB=80=E7=AE=97=E7=BB=8F), (<i>The Arithmetical Classic of the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnomon_(figure)" title=3D"Gnomon (fig=
ure)">Gnomon</a> and the Circular Paths of Heaven</i>) gives a reasoning fo=
r the Pythagorean theorem for the (3, 4, 5) triangle =E2=80=94 in China it =
is called the "<b>Gougu theorem</b>" (=E5=8B=BE=E8=82=A1=E5=AE=9A=E7=90=86)=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Crease_86-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Crease-86"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Cullen_87-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Cullen-87"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> During=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_Dynasty" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Han Dynasty">Han Dynasty</a> (202&nbsp;BC to 220&nbsp;AD), P=
ythagorean triples appear in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th=
e_Nine_Chapters_on_the_Mathematical_Art" title=3D"The Nine Chapters on the =
Mathematical Art">The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art</a></i>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Hui_88-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Hui-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> together with a =
mention of right triangles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Shen_89-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-S=
hen-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Some believe the theorem arose first in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China" title=3D"China">China</a> in the 11th cent=
ury BC,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Centaurus_90-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Centaurus-90"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> where it is alternatively known as the "<b>Shang Gao theorem</b>"=
 (=E5=95=86=E9=AB=98=E5=AE=9A=E7=90=86),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CY_Chen_91-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_the=
orem#cite_note-CY_Chen-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> named after the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duke_of_Zhou" title=3D"Duke of Zhou">Duke of Zhou's</a=
> astronomer and mathematician, whose reasoning composed most of what was i=
n the <i>Zhoubi Suanjing</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wu_92-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-W=
u-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
